In .NET 10 (starting with .NET 9 SR10+), `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated on Android because the underlying `adjustResize` mode was removed by Android itself (API 30+).

The recommended replacement is to use **Edge-to-Edge** mode with `KeyboardAcceleratorsInsets` / the new `InputTransparency` APIs, or more practically:

## Recommended fix

Use `Android:Window.SoftInputMode="AdjustPan"` combined with wrapping your page content in a `ScrollView`, or better yet, handle insets explicitly:

### Option 1 – AdjustPan (simplest)

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
[Activity(..., WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustPan)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

This scrolls the entire window up so the focused input stays visible.

### Option 2 – Edge-to-Edge with insets (recommended for .NET 10)

.NET 10 embraces Android's edge-to-edge model. Add padding that reacts to the keyboard inset:

```xml
<!-- Your page -->
<Grid x:Name="Root" Padding="0">
    <!-- Chat messages -->
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ... />

    <!-- Input bar -->
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" x:Name="InputBar">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

In your Android platform code, listen to insets:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        // imeInsets.Bottom gives keyboard height in pixels
        // Raise your input bar by setting bottom margin/padding
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, imeInsets.Bottom);
        return insets;
    }
}
```

### TL;DR

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| `AdjustPan` | One line, works immediately | Whole screen pans; less control |
| Edge-to-edge insets | Precise, modern, animatable | More code, Android-only |

For a chat screen, **Option 1 (`AdjustPan`)** is usually sufficient. If you need the chat list to shrink (not pan), go with **Option 2** and animate the bottom padding to match the keyboard height.
